\begin_layout Left Header
Flow-id: 70
\end_layout

\begin_layout Right Header
4394: Financial Econometrics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Title
Exam 2022
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Flow-id: 70
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Newpage pagebreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Theoretical part
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the Nonlinear Asymmetric GARCH (NAGARCH) model of Engle and Ng
 (1993) defined by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}y_{t} & =\sigma_{t}\varepsilon_{t}\\
\sigma_{t}^{2} & =\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-1}+\gamma\right)^{2}+\beta\sigma_{t-1}^{2},
\end{aligned}
\text{}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\in\mathbb{R},\alpha>0,\beta\geq0$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{t}$
\end_inset

 is independent and identically distributed (iid) over time with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\left[\varepsilon_{t}\right]=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\left[\varepsilon_{t}^{2}\right]=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
[Note that, the NAGARCH model is similar to the Asymmetric GARCH model of
 Engel (1990) which postulates 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{t}^{2}=\omega+\left(\alpha y_{t-1}+\gamma\right)^{2}+\beta\sigma_{t-1}^{2}$
\end_inset

 , i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{t-1}$
\end_inset

 is replaced by 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t-1}$
\end_inset

.]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
a) Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{t}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is initialized at the infinite past.
 Derive an expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{t}^{2}$
\end_inset

 as a function of all infinite past values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{t}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{t-1},\varepsilon_{t-2},\cdots$
\end_inset

.
 Call this quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $_{u}\sigma_{t}^{2}$
\end_inset

, where "
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

" stands for "unconditional" to stress that the process is not defined condition
al on some initial value.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
i) Derive conditions on 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega,\alpha,\gamma,\beta$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $_{u}\sigma_{t}^{2}>0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 For next points ii) and iii) assume these conditions are satisfied.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To derive an expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{t}^{2}$
\end_inset

 as a function of all infinite past values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{t}$
\end_inset

, we can start by writing 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sigma_{t}^{2} & =\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-1}+\gamma\right)^{2}+\beta\sigma_{t-1}^{2}\\
 & =\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-1}+\gamma\right)^{2}+\beta\left(\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-2}+\gamma\right)^{2}+\beta\sigma_{t-2}^{2}\right)\\
 & =\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-1}+\gamma\right)^{2}+\beta\left(\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-2}+\gamma\right)^{2}+\beta\left(\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-3}+\gamma\right)^{2}+\beta\sigma_{t-3}^{2}\right)\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then defining 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{t}\equiv\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t}+\gamma\right)^{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sigma_{t}^{2} & =\omega+\phi_{t-1}+\beta\left(\omega+\phi_{t-2}+\beta\left(\omega+\phi_{t-3}+\beta\sigma_{t-3}^{2}\right)\right)\\
 & =\omega+\phi_{t-1}+\beta\omega+\beta\phi_{t-2}+\beta^{2}\left(\omega+\phi_{t-3}+\beta\sigma_{t-3}^{2}\right)\\
 & =\omega+\phi_{t-1}+\beta\left(\omega+\phi_{t-2}\right)+\beta^{2}\left(\omega+\phi_{t-3}\right)+\beta^{3}\sigma_{t-3}^{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now it is evident that we have a pattern, which we can express as a sum
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma_{t}^{2}=\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}\beta^{j}\left(\omega+\phi_{t-j-1}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thereby we are conditioning on all infinite past observations, and we can
 utilize the unconditional notation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
_{u}\sigma_{t}^{2} & =\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}\beta^{j}\left(\omega+\phi_{t-j-1}\right)\\
 & =\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}\beta^{j}\left(\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-j-1}+\gamma\right)^{2}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta^{j}$
\end_inset

 is always positive, in order for the sum to be positive, it is necessary
 for the term 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-j-1}+\gamma\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

 to be positive for all
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To ensure that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-j-1}+\gamma\right)^{2}>0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, it is necessary for 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{t-j-1}+\gamma$
\end_inset

 can take on any value, it is not possible to derive further conditions
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 that would guarantee that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-j-1}+\gamma\right)^{2}>0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, the necessary conditions on 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $_{u}\sigma_{t}^{2}>0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega>0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta>0$
\end_inset

 .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
ii) Derive conditions on 
\begin_inset Formula $(\omega,\alpha,\gamma,\beta)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\left[_{u}\sigma_{t}^{2}\right]<\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\left[_{u}\sigma_{t}^{2}\right]$
\end_inset

 under these conditions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To ensure that the expectation of 
\begin_inset Formula $_{u}\sigma_{t}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is finite, we must have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{E}\left[_{u}\sigma_{t}^{2}\right]=\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}\beta^{j}\mathbb{E}\left[\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-j-1}+\gamma\right)^{2}\right]<\infty
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The term 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\left[\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-j-1}+\gamma\right)^{2}\right]$
\end_inset

 is finite if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-j-1}+\gamma\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

 are finite.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{t-j-1}$
\end_inset

 is a random variable with a finite mean, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{t-j-1}+\gamma$
\end_inset

 is finite if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is finite.
 Therefore, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 finite in order to ensure that the expectation of 
\begin_inset Formula $_{u}\sigma_{t}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is finite.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Furthermore, for the series 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}\beta^{j}\mathbb{E}\left[\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-j-1}+\gamma\right)^{2}\right]$
\end_inset

 to converge, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mid\beta\mid<1$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, it must be ensured that 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\in\mathbb{R}^{+}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\in\mathbb{R}^{+}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in\mathbb{R}^{+}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $0<\beta<1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then under these conditions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbb{E}\left[_{u}\sigma_{t}^{2}\right] & =\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}\beta^{j}\mathbb{E}\left[\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-j-1}+\gamma\right)^{2}\right]\\
 & =\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}\beta^{j}\mathbb{E}\left[\omega\right]+\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}\beta^{j}\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-j-1}+\gamma\right)^{2}\\
 & =\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}\beta^{j}\omega+\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}\beta^{j}\alpha\mathbb{E}\left[\varepsilon_{t-j-1}^{2}+\gamma^{2}+2\gamma\varepsilon_{t-j-1}\right]
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\left[\varepsilon_{t}^{2}\right]=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\left[\varepsilon_{t}\right]=0$
\end_inset

, thus
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbb{E}\left[_{u}\sigma_{t}^{2}\right] & =\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}\beta^{j}\omega+\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}\beta^{j}\alpha\mathbb{E}\left[1+\gamma^{2}\right]\\
 & =\frac{\omega+\alpha\left(1+\gamma^{2}\right)}{1-\beta}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
iii) Is it problematic if 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta<1$
\end_inset

 ? How is this case different from the 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{GARCH}(1,1)$
\end_inset

 model of Bollerslev (1986)?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to Nelson (1990) Theorem 1.(a):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $_{u}\sigma_{t}^{2}=0$
\end_inset

 almost surely, however from point i) under the assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=0$
\end_inset

, however we can 
\series bold
not
\series default
 ensure 
\begin_inset Formula $_{u}\sigma_{t}^{2}>0$
\end_inset

, since
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
_{u}\sigma_{t}^{2} & =\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}\beta^{j}\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-j-1}+\gamma\right)^{2}\\
 & ≥0
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Having 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta<1$
\end_inset

 ensures 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\left[_{u}\sigma_{t}^{2}\right]<\infty$
\end_inset

, thus this does not cause additional problems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
b) Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{t}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is initialized at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

 at the value 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{0}^{2}>0$
\end_inset

.
 Derive an expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{t}^{2}$
\end_inset

 as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{0}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and past values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{t}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{t-1},\varepsilon_{t-2},\ldots,\varepsilon_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
i) What is the difference between 
\begin_inset Formula $_{u}\sigma_{t}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{t}^{2}$
\end_inset

? Under which condition on 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $_{u}\sigma_{t}^{2}-\sigma_{t}^{2}\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $t\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 ?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The difference is that 
\begin_inset Formula $_{u}\sigma_{t}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is the process that goes back to the infinite past, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{t}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is a finite process.
 Consider:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sigma_{t}^{2} & =\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-1}+\gamma\right)^{2}+\beta\sigma_{t-1}^{2}\\
 & =\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-1}+\gamma\right)^{2}+\beta\left(\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-2}+\gamma\right)^{2}+\beta\sigma_{t-2}^{2}\right)\\
 & =\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-1}+\gamma\right)^{2}+\beta\left(\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-2}+\gamma\right)^{2}+\beta\left(\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-3}+\gamma\right)^{2}+\beta\sigma_{t-3}^{2}\right)\right)\\
 & =\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-1}+\gamma\right)^{2}+\beta\left(\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-2}+\gamma\right)^{2}+\beta\left(\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-3}+\gamma\right)^{2}+\beta\sigma_{t-3}^{2}\right)\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
defining 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{t}\equiv\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t}+\gamma\right)^{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sigma_{t}^{2} & =\omega+\phi_{t-1}+\beta\left(\omega+\phi_{t-2}+\beta\left(\omega+\phi_{t-3}+\beta\sigma_{t-3}^{2}\right)\right)\\
 & =\omega+\phi_{t-1}+\beta\omega+\beta\phi_{t-2}+\beta^{2}\left(\omega+\phi_{t-3}+\beta\sigma_{t-3}^{2}\right)\\
 & =\omega+\phi_{t-1}+\beta\left(\omega+\phi_{t-2}\right)+\beta^{2}\left(\omega+\phi_{t-3}\right)+\beta^{3}\sigma_{t-3}^{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and so on until 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{0}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma_{t}^{2}=\sigma_{0}^{2}\beta^{t}+\sum_{j=0}^{t-1}\beta^{j}\left(\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-j-1}+\gamma\right)^{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then to obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $_{u}\sigma_{t}^{2}-\sigma_{t}^{2}\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

, we must have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\lim_{t\rightarrow\infty}{}_{u}\sigma_{t}^{2}-\sigma_{t}^{2}\rightarrow & 0\\
\lim_{t\rightarrow\infty}\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}\beta^{j}\left(\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-j-1}+\gamma\right)^{2}\right)-\sigma_{0}^{2}\beta^{t}+\sum_{j=0}^{t-1}\beta^{j}\left(\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-j-1}+\gamma\right)^{2}\right) & \rightarrow0\\
\lim_{t\rightarrow\infty}\sum_{j=t}^{\infty}\beta^{j}\left(\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-j-1}+\gamma\right)^{2}\right) & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which is satisfied iff
\begin_inset Formula $\mid\beta\mid<1$
\end_inset

.
 The condition 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq\beta<1$
\end_inset

 satisfies this.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
ii) What is the minimum value that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{t}^{2}$
\end_inset

 can achieve? Remember the geometric series: 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{h=0}^{n-1}r^{k}=\left(\frac{1-r^{n}}{1-r}\right)$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $r\neq1$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}\sum_{h=0}^{n-1}r^{k}=\frac{1}{1-r}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $|r|<1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{arg min }\sigma_{0}^{2}\beta^{t}+\sum_{j=0}^{t-1}\beta^{j}\left(\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-j-1}+\gamma\right)^{2}\right)=\text{arg min }\left(\varepsilon_{t-j-1}+\gamma\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{t-j-1}=-\gamma$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{inf }\sigma_{t}^{2} & =\sigma_{0}^{2}\beta^{t}+\sum_{j=0}^{t-1}\beta^{j}\left(\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-j-1}+\gamma\right)^{2}\right)\\
 & =\sigma_{0}^{2}\beta^{t}+\sum_{j=0}^{t-1}\beta^{j}\omega\\
 & =\sigma_{0}^{2}\beta^{t}+\frac{\omega}{1-\beta}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall, that we assume 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq\beta<1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{t\rightarrow\infty}\left(\sigma_{0}^{2}\beta^{t}\right)=0$
\end_inset

, thus
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{inf }\sigma_{t}^{2}=\frac{\omega}{1-\beta}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which is equivalent to the lower bound of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{GARCH}(1,1)$
\end_inset

 process, when 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega<0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\left[\ln\left(\beta+\alpha z_{t}^{2}\right)<0\right]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
c) Derive and discuss the News Impact Curve (NIC) for the NAGARCH model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The News Impact Curve (NIC) for the NAGARCH model is given by the conditional
 variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{t}^{2}$
\end_inset

 as a function of the past squared shocks 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{t-1}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, the NIC for the NAGARCH model is given by the following expression:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sigma_{t}^{2}\left(\varepsilon_{t-1}^{2}\right) & =\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-1}+\gamma\right)^{2}+\beta\sigma_{t-1}^{2}\\
 & =\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-1}^{2}+\gamma^{2}+2\varepsilon_{t-1}\gamma\right)+\beta\sigma_{t-1}^{2}\\
 & =\omega+\alpha\gamma^{2}+\beta\sigma_{t-1}^{2}+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-1}^{2}+2\varepsilon_{t-1}\gamma\right)\\
 & =A+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-1}^{2}+2\varepsilon_{t-1}\gamma\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $A\equiv\omega+\alpha\gamma^{2}+\beta\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the NAGARCH model, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 determines the magnitude of shocks on the volatility.
 A larger 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 will result in a larger impact of news on the volatility.
 The NAGARCH model extends the standard GARCH model by allowing for asymmetry
 in the response of the conditional variance to positive and negative shocks.
 This is achieved through the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, which allows the model to capture the asymmetry in the relationship between
 the past squared shocks and the current conditional variance.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 allows us the model differences between positive and negative news, as
 evident from figure 1.1.
 This figure shows a News Impact Curve for different parameters of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, where we see the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 determines the shifts of the curve.
 A high positive 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 will, ceteris paribus, result in higher volatility for no shocks, and the
 volatility will even decrease with negative shocks.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
