\begin_layout Standard
It is evident that the forecasted volatility initially is high, due to the
 fact that the last periods in the dataset shows high volatility, and the
 forecast consequently approaches the limit found in 
\shape italic
1.d)
\shape default
 quickly, as represented by the dashed line at 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=\sqrt{\frac{\omega+\alpha\left(1+\gamma^{2}\right)}{1-\beta}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
c) Write a function that estimates the NAGARCH-in-mean specification defined
 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}y_{t} & =\delta\log\sigma_{t}+\sigma_{t}\varepsilon_{t},\\
\sigma_{t}^{2} & =\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-1}+\gamma\right)^{2}+\beta\sigma_{t-1}^{2},
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

 Do not impose any constraint on the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

.
 As before, set the initial value of the process to the empirical variance
 of the data.
 Note that here 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{t}=\left(y_{t}-\delta\log\sigma_{t}\right)/\sigma_{t}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The mean of the model is then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbb{E}\left[y_{t}\right] & =\mathbb{E}\left[\delta\log\sigma_{t}+\sigma_{t}\varepsilon_{t}\right]\\
 & =\mathbb{E}\left[\delta\log\sigma_{t}\right]+\mathbb{E}\left[\sigma_{t}\varepsilon_{t}\right]\\
 & =\delta\log\sigma_{t}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with a corresponding variance of
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{Var}\left(y_{t}\right) & =\mathbb{E}\left[y_{t}^{2}\right]-\mathbb{E}\left[y_{t}\right]^{2}\\
 & =\mathbb{E}\left[\left(\delta\log\sigma_{t}+\sigma_{t}\varepsilon_{t}\right)^{2}\right]-\left(\delta\log\sigma_{t}\right)^{2}\\
 & =\sigma_{t}^{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
See the attached code.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Empirical Part
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
a) Estimate the NAGARCH model on each series.
 Show in a plot the empirical distribution of the estimated 
\begin_inset Formula $β$
\end_inset

 parameter across all series.
 What can you conclude about the persistence of the variance process for
 the components of the Dow Jones index?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename /Users/tobiasbrammer/Library/Mobile Documents/com~apple~CloudDocs/Documents/Aarhus Uni/7. semester/FinancialEconometrics/Exam2022/img/dji30ret_beta.pdf
	lyxscale 50
	width 50page%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Distribution of the estimated 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 parameter
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 represents the degree of persistence in the variance process.
 A value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 close to 1 indicates that the variance process is highly persistent, meaning
 that the volatility at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is strongly influenced by the volatility at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t-1$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, a value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 close to 0 indicates that the variance process is less persistent, meaning
 that the volatility at time t is less influenced by the volatility at time
 
\begin_inset Formula $t-1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the empirical distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 for the components of the Dow Jones index has a median of 0.938, this suggests
 that the variance process for these components is highly persistent.
 In other words, the volatility of these components is likely to be strongly
 influenced by the volatility in the previous time period.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This high degree of persistence in the variance process may indicate that
 the variance process for these components is relatively stable over time,
 and that the components are relatively resistant to changes in the underlying
 market conditions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
c) Estimate the NAGARCH-in-mean model on each series.
 Show in a plot the empirical distribution of the estimated 
\begin_inset Formula $δ$
\end_inset

 parameter across all series.
 What can you conclude about the so-called “volatility premium” in this
 dataset?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 in the 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\text{NAGARCH-in-mean}$
\end_inset


\series default
 model represents the the volatility premium of assets, which refers to
 the relationship between the volatility of a time series and the expected
 returns of the underlying asset.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A positive value of delta indicates that there is a positive relationship
 between volatility and expected returns, i.e.
 and increased volatility results in increased returns.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand, a negative value of delta indicates that there is a negative
 relationship between volatility and expected returns, which is referred
 to as a volatility discount.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the empirical estimations of 
\begin_inset Formula $δ$
\end_inset

 for the data shows a median value of 0.08, we could draw conclusions that
 there is generally little or no relationship between volatility and expected
 returns in the data.
 We would, however, need to test the statistical significance to draw a
 formal conclusion.
\end_layout

