\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Volatility forecast for 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{JPM}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall from lecture 4 slide 24:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The variance of a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\text{\textbf{GARCH}}\left(1,1\right)}$
\end_inset

-model can be represented as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma_{t}^{2}=\omega+\alpha r_{t-1}^{2}+\beta\sigma_{t-1}^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and thus
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\lim_{h\rightarrow\infty}E\left[\sigma_{t+h}^{2}\mid\mathcal{F}_{t}\right] & =\frac{\omega}{1-\alpha-\beta}+\lim_{h\rightarrow\infty}\left(\alpha+\beta\right)^{h-1}\left[\sigma_{t+1}^{2}-\sigma^{2}\right]\\
 & =\frac{\omega}{1-\alpha-\beta}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From point 
\shape italic
1.d) 
\shape default
the 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\text{NAGARCH}$
\end_inset


\series default
 follows 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\lim_{h\rightarrow\infty}E\left[\sigma_{t+h}^{2}\mid\mathcal{F}_{t}\right] & =\lim_{h\rightarrow\infty}\beta^{h-1}\sigma_{t+1}^{2}+\left(\omega+\alpha\left(1+\gamma^{2}\right)\right)\lim_{h\rightarrow\infty}\sum_{i=0}^{h-2}\beta^{i}\\
 & =\frac{\omega+\alpha\left(1+\gamma^{2}\right)}{1-\beta}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We see that the forecast of the 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\text{NAGARCH}$
\end_inset

 
\series default
converges to the mean-variance faster than the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\text{\textbf{GARCH}}\left(1,1\right)}$
\end_inset

-model, due to the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\alpha+\beta\right)>\beta$
\end_inset

 and consequently 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta^{h-1}<\left(\alpha+\beta\right)^{h-1}$
\end_inset

, which then implies a lower persistence of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{t+1}^{2}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

